One of the most poignant sites in The Ann Frank House in Amsterdam must be the magazine pictures of the young Princesses Elizabeth and Margaret that Anna pasted to the walls of her bedroom. These are now preserved for posterity behind sheets of plastic. Who would have guessed that during the lifetime of Elizabeth, fascism would rear it's ugly head again? This time from the nation that helped liberate Europe from The Nazis; the perpetrator from that era (Germany) now the sanctuary for those fleeing war and persecution elsewhere. Not a direct parallel - you can never step in the same river twice - but we live in the post-Nazi world where we've supposed to have learned the lessons of that era and we expect human life and dignity to have much more value. A real stark irony. Now Elizabeth has to play host to this man; a consequence of populist policies that led to The Brexit and the need to pursue trade deals. Trump may not be Hitler, but he is defining a new era of fascism that will forever be synonymous with his name. It's not too late to stop it.

People pay money for a professional sport and to watch a professional sport. People make professional sports possible, in that without having fans to watch the sport, the professional part of the sport ceases to exist. The players are paid to play the sport that the fans have paid to watch. The players are just filling a role in the whole scene. In no way should an athlete use time the fans are making possible to make a personal or political statement. That is not part of the purchase and should not make it's way into the game. Off the field - do what you want. On the field, your role is play the games the fans have made possible, and speaking of making things possible, consider your role in the equation when you cash your check. You work for the fans. Give us what we want and that is to watch professional sports.
